Security Operations Fundamentals > [T2]: Using Honeypots and Decoys for Defense

Honeypots and Tokens

One of our responsibilities as defenders is slowing down attackers and their malicious activities, and that's where honeypots fit most. But what is a honeypot? 

Honeypots are decoy systems that defenders deploy next to production systems within the network. They can be anything from simulation software to a full decoy, high-interaction system. They provide two essential things; detecting attackers and slowing them down. 

According to TechTarget: 

A honeypot is a network-attached system set up as a decoy to lure cyberattacks and detect, deflect and study hacking attempts to gain unauthorized access to information systems. 

Honeypots detect attackers because they act as live sensors inside your network. Imagine the attackers were able to compromise a system inside your network; the first thing they will probably do is explore the network -using scanning techniques- and look for high-value targets (e.g., database, confidential data, etc.). If a honeypot exists, it will alert for the scan attempt and reveal the attacker's activities. Remember, any connection attempt to a honeypot system is deemed illegal because a honeypot does not serve anything legit, and its sole purpose is to alert any interaction/activity. 

A honeypot slows down the attack by misdirecting the intruder. From an attacker's perspective, a honeypot will look identical to other real and legit systems. It will have an IP address in the default network range, respond to connection requests, and sometimes offer high-interaction functions to trick the attacker into thinking it's a real system. 

Honeypots are the tools we, as defenders, use to perform what we call "Active defense." Active defense is a term introduced by the US Department of Defense (DoD). It refers to slowing down adversaries' activities and making their mission harder. The active defense proactive strategy helps organizations discover cyber-attacks in the early stages. 

 

System and Service level honeypots

A famous example of a honeypot is "kippo," a medium interaction SSH honeypot designed to log brute-force attacks and, most importantly, the entire shell interaction performed by the attacker. From the outside, it will look precisely like an SSH server. If the attackers try to log in, it will log all interactions and present them to the defender. It's like watching over the attackers' shoulders what they type, when, and in what order! Check out this example of an attacker's activities on a Kippo honeypot!

Some honeypots are more advanced and offer more features and capabilities, such as MHN, a centralized server for the management and data collection of honeypots. MHN allows you to deploy sensors quickly and to collect data immediately, viewable from a neat web interface. MHN has the option to install many honeypots, such as Cowrie, Dionaea, and Glastopf.

 

Decoys and Canary Tokens

Decoy Bird

A decoy is a bird or mammal, or an imitation of one, used by hunters to attract other birds or mammals. In a defense context, a decoy/canary is a device, file, or other resources monitored for access. Once the resource has been accessed, an alert is triggered, notifying the object owner of said access. To learn more about decoy devices and files, check the following: Baiting Inside Attackers Using Decoy Documents.
 
A decoy/canary token can be anything like a fake database, confidential documents, passwords, etc. For example, defenders can create a fake document, give it an enticing name (such as top-secret.docx), and place it next to authentic documents. Any time this document gets opened, the security team gets notified instantly about the source IP of the attacker. In the next lab, we will see how this works in real life!
